The National Population Commission (NPC) has lamented the high level of infants’ deaths in the country, pointing out that an average of 132 deaths is being recorded per 1, 000 births. This was according to the Acting chairman of the commission, Bimbola Salu-Hundeyin on Tuesday while addressing journalists in Bauchi on the commencement of data collection for the 2019 Verbal and Social Autopsy (VASA) survey in the state. Represented by the national commissioner of the commission in charge of Bauchi and Gombe states, Abubakar Danburam, the NPC boss said every available tool must be deployed to combat and curb the menace in order to save the lives of coming generation. He explained that the objectives of the survey was to obtain data to determine the causes and contributory factors to deaths in children aged zero to five. According to him, the 2019 edition of the Verbal and Social Autopsy survey is the second in the series conducted by the commission after the one carried out in 2014. ” There is no gainsaying the fact that under 5 mortality in Nigeria is very high with an average of 132 deaths per 1, 000 births. What needs to be done is that every available tool must be deployed to combat and curb the menace in our society. ” I am very optimistic that the data will be used by policymakers and other stakeholders to formulate policies, design and implement programmes that will go a long way in reducing Neonatal and child mortality to the barest minimum in Nigeria, ” he stated. Download Daily Post App.    Subscribe to Daily Post Newsletter.    Advertise with us.   Send us enquiries, press releases.